      "visualKind": "shape",
      "title": "<h1>The Comet's Secret</h1><p>Luna was a curious child who loved fixing broken things. In her backyard workshop, she had built something special: a small spaceship with a glowing engine she made from old parts and dreams.</p><p>One night, a bright comet streaked across the sky. It was different from other comets. This one sparkled with colors Luna had never seen before—purple, green, and silver all mixed together. The comet seemed to be calling to her.</p><p>\"I have to follow it,\" Luna whispered.</p><p>She climbed into her spaceship and started the engine. It hummed to life, lifting her up past the clouds and into space. The stars twinkled around her like a million tiny lanterns lighting her way.</p><p>The comet moved fast, but Luna's engine was clever. It could sense where the comet wanted to go. As she flew closer, the comet's tail grew brighter and brighter. Then something amazing happened.</p><p>The comet opened a doorway.</p><p>Luna flew through it and gasped. She had entered an alternative dimension where everything was backwards and forwards at the same time. Stars here didn't just shine—they sang. The darkness was made of soft velvet that felt warm, not cold.</p><p>In this strange new place, the comet finally stopped. It wasn't just a comet at all. It was a messenger. The comet spoke without words, filling Luna's mind with pictures and feelings. It showed her that some things are impossible in one world but perfectly normal in another.</p><p>\"You can fix anything,\" the comet seemed to say, \"even broken dreams. Your engine brought you here because you believed it could.\"</p><p>Luna smiled. She understood. The engine worked because she never stopped being curious. The alternative dimension existed because she dared to follow something mysterious.</p><p>When the comet sent her home, Luna's spaceship glided back through the doorway. Space looked different now. The stars seemed friendlier, like they were all keeping the same wonderful secret.</p><p>Back in her yard, Luna looked up at the night sky. The comet was gone, but she knew it would return someday. And when it did, she'd be ready for another adventure.</p><p>Her little engine hummed quietly, already dreaming of the next impossible journey.</p>"
    },
